item.title: Virgin Atlantic to cut 3000 jobs
item.description: British airline Virgin Atlantic plans to cut 3150 jobs and move its flying program from London Gatwick to Heathrow airport as it counts the cost of the COVID-19 pandemic.

item.title: German court objects to ECB bond purchases
item.description: Germany's Constitutional Court has upheld several complaints against the European Central Bank's purchase of government bonds under a program designed to boost inflation and the economy since 2015.

item.title: No virus spike after Austrian reopening
item.description: Austria's first loosening of its coronavirus lockdown three weeks ago, in which thousands of shops reopened, has not led to a new spike in infections, though further vigilance is necessary, its health minister says.

item.title: Two dead in Liberia mine collapse
item.description: Liberia's assistant mines minister says two miners hav died in a mine collapse in western Liberia, although a local mayor estimates scores more are likely dead based on the number of people missing.

item.title: China launches new-generation spacecraft
item.description: China has successfully launched its largest carrier rocket, which was carrying a new-generation spacecraft, state broadcaster CCTV says.

item.title: RAF jets bomb Islamic State caves in Iraq
item.description: RAF fighter jets have bombed six caves being used as a base for Islamic State militants in northern Iraq.

item.title: Philippines orders TV network to shut
item.description: A Philippine government agency has ordered the country's leading broadcast network, which the president has targeted for its critical news coverage, to halt operations.

item.title: Early French virus case found
item.description: A French study suggesting a man in France was infected with COVID-19 as early as December 27, nearly a month before the country confirmed its first cases, could be important in assessing when and where the virus emerged, experts say.

item.title: Israeli raid kills fighters: Syria monitor
item.description: At least 14 Iranian armed forces and allied militia members have been killed in an Israeli aerial attack on their posts in eastern Syria, a monitoring group says.

item.title: UK has Europe’s highest virus death toll
item.description: Britain has overtaken Italy to report the highest official death toll from coronavirus in Europe with more than 32,000 deaths, new figures show.
